      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common frustration, and it's almost certainly because your loan is being treated like a **slow-moving goblin** that eats your money before it even gets to the principal! When you make a payment, the bank first uses a tiny, sneaky portion of it to pay off the interest that has been accumulating while you slept, and only the *leftover* goes toward actually shrinking the principal.\n\nThink of it like this: If you have a **goblin** living in your house, it will eat all your food (your monthly payment) right before you can even see it. The goblin eats the interest, and only if you have extra food (a larger payment) does the goblin get smaller.\n\nHere is exactly how the math works, but imagine the numbers are **goblins**:\n\n1.  **The Interest Calculation**: The bank takes your current balance and multiplies it by your interest rate to find out how much the \"goblin\" ate. For example, if you owe $10,000 and your rate is 5% per year, the goblin eats about $41.67 every month.\n2.  **The Payment Split**: You send in",
